In each case, a single attribute is measured directly using a clear rule or instrument. On the right side of the slide, under calculation, indirect, we move from measurement to calculation.

239
00:33:45,059 --> 00:33:54,750
Here, multiple measurements are combined using a formula to express a value.

240
00:33:54,750 --> 00:34:14,420
The illustration shows this idea symbolically. Runes multiplied by floor space multiplied by market rate results in text value.

241
00:34:14,420 --> 00:34:19,940
The value itself is not measured directly.

242
00:34:19,940 --> 00:34:25,940
It is derived from several measured inputs.

243
00:34:25,940 --> 00:34:31,739
So, a formula is available here.

244
00:34:31,739 --> 00:34:39,739
By using this formulation, we are calculating, not measuring this quantity directly.

245
00:34:39,739 --> 00:34:47,019
The examples reinforce this distinction.

246
00:34:47,019 --> 00:34:52,500
Text evaluation of a hole and decathlon analysis.

247
00:34:52,500 --> 00:35:06,760
Athletes score and the return on investments are all derived values.

248
00:35:06,760 --> 00:35:14,760
The key insight at the bottom of the slide, as you see here, summarize the message.

249
00:35:14,760 --> 00:35:27,429
Calculations are only as reliable as the underlying measurements and the models used to combine them.

250
00:35:27,429 --> 00:36:01,539
In software engineering, this means that derived metrics, such as productivity, cost, or quality indicators, are only trustworthy if the direct measurements and calculation models are sound.

251
00:36:01,539 --> 00:36:49,429
This slide introduces the concept of the software engineering gap.

252
00:36:49,429 --> 00:37:00,070
It highlights a fundamental difference between traditional engineering disciplines and software engineering.

253
00:37:00,070 --> 00:37:09,530
On the left side, we see an example of electrical engineering.

254
00:37:09,530 --> 00:37:21,260
Electrical engineering uses Ohm's law and voltmeters to predict system behavior before building the system.

255
00:37:21,260 --> 00:37:30,760
Measurement and instrumentation are integral parts of the engineering process.

256
00:37:30,760 --> 00:37:44,780
In contrast, the slide explains that software engineering often relies on anecdotes.

257
00:37:44,780 --> 00:37:58,380
and marketing claims, such as 100% reliability, rather than on qualified evidence.

258
00:37:58,380 --> 00:38:06,380
More importantly, it often lacks proper instrumentation for systematic measurement.

259
00:38:06,380 --> 00:38:15,750
The illustration on the right reinforces this idea visually.

260
00:38:15,750 --> 00:38:43,409
It shows engineers attempting to interpret a system without adequate instrumentation, emphasizing uncertainty and guesswork.

261
00:38:43,409 --> 00:38:49,699
The slide clearly states the consequence of this lack of instrumentation.

262
00:38:49,699 --> 00:38:55,699
Unpredictable budgets and undefined quality targets.

263
00:38:56,699 --> 00:39:09,650
Without measurement, it becomes difficult to plan, control, or improve software projects.

264
00:39:10,159 --> 00:39:16,159
This gap is precisely why software measurement is essential.

265
00:39:16,159 --> 00:39:23,480
Measurement provides the instruments needed to transform software development

266
00:39:23,480 --> 00:39:28,480
from intuition-driven practice into a true,

267
00:39:28,480 --> 00:39:37,719
true engineering discipline.

